comments.body:
@iSazonov It's ok to say "we don't have the resources to do an RFC for everything" ...

It's **not** ok to create a breaking changes contract and then ignore it.

It's not ok, _in any product_ that has a beta cycle, to make **breaking changes** _after_ the beta cycle. That's **just _plain_ wrong**. If this team is going to do that, then PowerShell will become an undependable, unusable product.

@SteveL-MSFT I acknowledge it went through code review (very quickly, and at the last minute). If you want to throw someone else under the bus, feel free :wink:. It's not my intention to lambast you as if you were saving this secret change until the last minute and sneaking it in to deliberately make things more painful. If you like, my problem is that _the whole team_ allowed a rather egregious violation of process.  This is a bucket 1, public contract, breaking change. It was done **despite** prior community discussions which had resulted in the change being rejected, and it was done without any pre-release.  

I disagree with the argument that it's easier to put it back later than to take it out later, but even if I agreed, that's a *terrible* reason to make a breaking change that late in the development cycle.

FWIW the ability to whitelist aliases was added to PSSA:
```
Rules = @{
    # Do not flag 'cd' alias.
    PSAvoidUsingCmdletAliases = @{Whitelist = @('cd')}
}
```
